<div class="aboutCopy">
    <h2>The Mayan Calendar</h2>
    <p>
Dates recorded in the Mayan Calendar are one of the most common examples of Classical Mayan hieroglyphic writing.
Beautifully sculpted in the limestone of temple stairs and stelae, or expertly scribed upon ceramic ware and paper-bark codices, they fix in time the birth of kings and the conquest of foes. A Mayan Calendar date consists of an array of hieroglyphs, and can contain information such as the lunar phase, the position of the day in 5-, 7-, and 819-day cycles, and various associated colours and patron deities. 
    <br /> <br />
Almost invariably, however, Mayan dates contain two key features:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>The <i>Long Count</i>, which fixes the date's position in an eternal linear continuum, and</li>
        <li>The <i>Calendar Round</i>, which comprises the sacred <i>Tzolk'in</i> cycle and the <i>Haab'</i> solar year.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
This website converts between a Gregorian Date and a Mayan Date with a Long Count, Calendar Round, and a supplementary 9-day cycle called the <i>Lord of the Night</i>*.
    </p>
    <div class="aside">
* The term "Lord of the Night" is an invention; the glyphs in question are followed by a glyph translated as <b>TI-HUN'-(na)</b>, "Reader of the Book". Epigraphers have a propensity for inventiveness, which often means that names used to describe the Mayan Calendar have no relationship whatever to what the Mayans actually wrote. Indeed, the terms "Tzolk'in" and "Haab'" are borrowed from modern dialects, as are the names of the glyphs they contain; in some cases, we have no idea what the Classical Mayan terms for these dates were.
    </div>
</div>

