    <h2>The Long Count</h2>
    <p>
The Long Count records the time elapsed, in days, since the day of creation, believed by Mayan Scholars to be 11 August 3114 BCE. The Mayans count in vigesimal, or base 20; each glyph of the Long Count consists of a digit and a glyph to mark the place. The Long Count is vigesimal with one exception -- the second digit, which counts 20-day increments, resets after 18; thus approximating solar years by allowing the higher places to count in increments of 360 days.
<br /><br />
Long Count dates are shown, like our number system, with the most significant digit first, followed by the next most significant, down to the last digit which counts days by the each. Most Long Counts contain five places -- days, scores of days, years, scores of years, and "bundles" -- scores of scores of years. There is, however, no limit on how many digits a Long Count can contain.
<br /><br />
Some Long Count dates use the number 13 in higher places to represent the date of creation, such as Coba Stela 1, which has a Long Count date of 13.13.13.13.13.13.13.13.13.13.13.13.13.13.13.13.13.13.13.13.0.0.0.0. It is unknown whether this refers to a date in the unimaginably distant future, or is merely a way to impress upon the reader the limitless nature of the Mayan understanding of cyclic time.
    </p>
</div>

