<div class="aboutCopy">
    <h2>The Haab'</h2>
    <p>
The Haab' is a solar year of 365 days, divided into 18 months of 20 days each. In contrast to the Tzolk'in, the Haab' is a more commonplace calendar, detailing seasonal and agricultural information. Each month begins with a zero-day called the "seating", in which the patron deity of the month would be ceremonially installed.
<br /><br />
The astute observer will note that 18 months of 20 days is only 360 days total; the Mayans, with their love of perfect cycles and ratios, begrudgingly doled out the five extra days required to match the Earth's rotation around the sun. These five days, sited at the end of the year and called <i>Wayeb'</i>, or "the sleepers", were immensely unlucky; the Mayans did not, among other things, leave their homes or bathe during this time.
    </p>
</div>
